## 2. What Changes in React vs Plain HTML

This is the most important section to understand before starting.

### The core idea

In plain HTML, every page is a separate file.
In React, there is ONE html file and ONE JavaScript app.
React swaps out what you see on screen by showing/hiding components.
No page reloads. No separate files per page.

### Side by side comparison

```
PLAIN HTML WAY                    REACT WAY
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
18 separate .html files      →   18 page components in src/pages/
<script src="auth.js">       →   import { useAuth } from '../context/AuthContext'
window.location.href =       →   const navigate = useNavigate()
  'dashboard.html'                navigate('/dashboard')
document.getElementById()   →   const [value, setValue] = useState('')
onclick="handleLogin()"      →   onClick={handleLogin}
sessionStorage for state     →   React Context API
Manual DOM manipulation      →   State change = React re-renders automatically
Separate CSS per page        →   Import CSS at top of component file
```

### Real example — Login form

```html
<!-- OLD WAY (plain HTML) -->
<input id="loginEmail" type="email" />
<button onclick="handleLogin()">Login</button>
<script>
  function handleLogin() {
    const email = document.getElementById('loginEmail').value;
  }
</script>
```

```tsx
// NEW WAY (React + TypeScript)
const [email, setEmail] = useState<string>('');

function handleLogin() {
  console.log(email); // already has the value via state
}

return (
  <input
    type="email"
    value={email}
    onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
  />
  <button onClick={handleLogin}>Login</button>
);
```

