## 6. How State Works

### Local state — useState

For data inside one component (form inputs, toggles, selections):

```tsx
// Form input
const [email, setEmail] = useState<string>('');
const [password, setPassword] = useState<string>('');

// Selected role
const [selectedRole, setSelectedRole] = useState<string | null>(null);

// File upload
const [file, setFile] = useState<File | null>(null);
```

### Global state — Context API

For data shared across many pages (logged-in user, analysis result):

```tsx
// Any component can read the user
const { user, login, logout } = useAuth();

// Any component can read the analysis result
const { results, setResults } = useAnalysis();
```

### How old JS patterns become React state

```
OLD: sessionStorage.getItem('cl_user')
NEW: const { user } = useAuth();

OLD: sessionStorage.setItem('cl_role', role)
NEW: setSelectedRole(role)  in AnalysisContext

OLD: document.getElementById('score').textContent = '72%'
NEW: const [score, setScore] = useState(72)
     <div>{score}%</div>
```

---

## 7. How CSS Works

**Good news — all 8 CSS files from the old project are reused exactly.**
Zero changes to any CSS. Just copy them into src/assets/css/.

Import CSS at the top of each page component that needs it:

```tsx
// Landing.tsx
import '../assets/css/global.css';
import '../assets/css/landing.css';

// Dashboard.tsx
import '../assets/css/global.css';
import '../assets/css/dashboard.css';

// Login.tsx
import '../assets/css/global.css';
import '../assets/css/auth.css';
```

All class names stay exactly the same:
```tsx
// OLD HTML
<div class="db-stat-card fade-up delay-2">

// NEW React (class → className in JSX)
<div className="db-stat-card fade-up delay-2">
```

**Only one change: `class` becomes `className` in JSX.**
That is the only difference in how CSS works.

